Proposed Design Approach - Stateless Weighted Supplier Selection

1. Objective

The objective of this design is to remove runtime database updates from the phone verification supplier selection path and reduce database row-level lock contention during high-volume remote proofing transactions, especially for Change of Address.

The current implementation uses RP_KBA_ATTEMPTS.ATTEMPTS as a runtime counter and updates the selected supplier row for every transaction when split allocation is configured. Under high concurrency, multiple transactions attempt to update the same small set of rows, causing Oracle row-level locking, blocking sessions, delayed processing, and timeout errors.

The proposed design keeps the existing supplier allocation configuration in the database but changes the runtime supplier selection logic to use stateless weighted selection based on configured percentages.

⸻

2. High-Level Design Summary

The existing TOTAL_ATTEMPTS values in RP_KBA_ATTEMPTS will continue to represent configured supplier allocation percentages.

Example:

Sponsor: Change of Address
Proofing Level: 1
Supplier 5 - Equifax DIT SMFA  = 60
Supplier 4 - Lexis Nexis OTP   = 40

The proposed design will use these configured values as weights.

Instead of selecting the supplier by sorting on runtime ATTEMPTS and incrementing the selected supplier row, the application will generate a random number within the total configured weight and select the supplier based on the configured weighted range.

Example for 60/40 allocation:

Random value range: 0 - 99
0 - 59   -> Equifax DIT SMFA
60 - 99  -> Lexis Nexis OTP

This removes the need to update ATTEMPTS during runtime transaction processing.

